               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18370918-name-749" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18370918-name-749" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18370918-name-749" type="surname" value="NOBLE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18370918-name-749" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES NOBLE</persName>
                  </hi>. I live at Stepney. On the 6th of September the prisoner brought me two pictures—I had seen him before, twice—I bought them of him for 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., and he went away—he sold them as his own—he returned on the 19th—I had reason to suspect him then, and told him I must take him to the station-house—he immediately ran away—I pursued him, and he was stopped in my presence—I had hung the pictures out for sale, and they had been claimed.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18370918-name-750" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18370918-name-750" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18370918-name-750" type="surname" value="BENNETT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18370918-name-750" type="given" value="LUCY"></interp>LUCY BENNETT</persName>
                  </hi>. I am in the service of William Hallibruton, of the Crown and Anchor, Stall-street, Stepney. These pictures were in his drinking-parlour—the prisoner came on the 6th of September, and was not there more than half an hour—immediately after he was gone I missed the pictures—I am quite sure he is the man—these are the pictures.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence</hi>. I deny being in the house altogether—I purchased these pictures.</p>
